LOAD Exercise:

The C loadc.c code requests 16 threads, and iterates over a loop
that executes a load on the first set of 8 threads on EVEN 
iterations and the other set (last 8) on ODD iterations.

It is interesting to see a timeline of the load in a remora plot
and determine which threads are being used, and how much of a load
is being created by the other threads waiting at the barrier
(on each iteration in the parallel region).

In the remora_#####/CPU directory there are cpu_<nodeid>.* load files.


============================================================================


0.) Make sure you are in an interactive IDEV session, 
    then cd to the memory dir.

    If not, start a session:

       idev  # with appropriate reservation and account
       cd remora/load

       module load remora
       export REMORA_PERIOD=1   # *******

1.) Look over loadc.c, and the make the loadc executable.

       make

2.) Make sure the program runs:

       ./loadc

3.) Now run it with remora

       remora ./load

    a.) Which directory and files have the load information   (__________)  

        Copy (use scp) the cpu_<node>.html to your machine.
     or
        cat the file, select the output and paste it into load.html
        on your laptop.
           To open the single load.html file ON YOUR LOCAL machine:

            ON MACS:       open load.html
            ON LINUX:      open load.html  or firefox load.html
            ON Windows:    open load.html  or <click> on load.html

    b.) Validate that different cores are being used for each set
        of threads. (On a line hover over a data point dot.)
        Are they a sequential set  (-----------yes/no)
 
    c.) How much of a load are the "idle" threads actually put
        on the cores they are "idling" on?  (______%).
        Hint: note where the 100% load theads settle down to
        when the other set is running at 100% -- they don't settle
        down to 0%.

    d.) What is the average load on the system for this run? (___%)
        Hint: note the flat line near the bottom labeled "avg".

